  "issue_title": "[E1.9.3] Kernel-loss watchdog -> system SAFE_HALT (heartbeat timeout)",
  "issue_body": "## Context\nSAFE_HALT exists at the Kernel (#38) but is only triggered by an explicit `safety.halt`. If the **Kernel itself dies**, nothing detects its absence and the system can keep acting without the gate - the opposite of fail-closed. A watchdog must SAFE_HALT the system when the Kernel's heartbeat stops.\n\n## Goal\nA watchdog (in the launcher/supervisor) that monitors the Kernel heartbeat and, on a heartbeat timeout, drives the system into SAFE_HALT so no proposal can be acted on without the gate.\n\n## Scope (checklist)\n- [ ] Define/confirm a Kernel heartbeat (subject or liveness signal) and a timeout budget.\n- [ ] Watchdog in `launcher/` (or supervisor) that detects heartbeat loss.\n- [ ] On timeout: publish `safety.halt` (or invoke SAFE_HALT) so downstream defaults to DENY; record the cause.\n- [ ] Recovery: when the Kernel returns healthy, require explicit operator resume (`safety.resume`), not auto-resume.\n- [ ] Tests: kill the Kernel -> system SAFE_HALTs within the timeout; restart -> stays halted until resume.\n\n## Out of scope\nSafety-Supervisor-loss watchdog (E1.9.4); the SAFE_HALT UI button (E1.9.6, #70); halt/resume audit trail (E1.9.7).\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n- With the Kernel killed, the system enters SAFE_HALT within the timeout and proposals default to DENY.\n- Resume is operator-gated, never automatic.\n\n## Affected files / areas\n`launcher/`, supervisor, kernel heartbeat emit site, `launcher/tests/`.\n\n## Dependencies\nBuilds on #38 (SAFE_HALT). Pairs with E1.9.4. Relates to E1.9.6 (#70). Milestone M1.\n\n## Skills & effort\nPython async, supervision/watchdog, fail-closed reasoning. Effort **M**. Maintainer review required (safety).\n\n## Definition of Done\nWatchdog SAFE_HALT test green in CI; fail-closed-on-Kernel-loss documented; no invariant weakened; reviewed & merged to `dev`.\n\n---\nRoadmap: [ISSUES.md](ISSUES.md) - Phase 1 / Task 1.9b - E-ID **E1.9.3**",
